  "prompt": "What is creamy layer?",
  "response": "The term **\"creamy layer\"** refers to a concept used in the context of **reservation policies** in India. It identifies the relatively affluent and advanced individuals within the socially and educationally backward classes (such as Scheduled Castes (SCs), Scheduled Tribes (STs), and Other Backward Classes (OBCs)) who have benefited from reservation policies and no longer require additional affirmative action.\n\n### Key Points About the Creamy Layer:\n1. **Purpose**:  \n   The creamy layer concept aims to ensure that the benefits of reservation reach the **most disadvantaged** sections of society, rather than being monopolized by the better-off members within these groups.\n\n2. **Exclusion**:  \n   Individuals identified as part of the creamy layer are **excluded** from availing reservation benefits in jobs, education, and other areas.\n\n3. **Income Criteria**:  \n   In India, the creamy layer is determined based on **income thresholds**. As of recent updates, a family earning more than **\u20b98 lakh per annum** is considered part of the creamy layer for OBCs.\n\n4. **Historical Context**:  \n   The concept was introduced by the **Supreme Court of India** in the **Indra Sawhney case (1992)**, also known as the Mandal Commission case, which upheld 27% reservation for OBCs in government jobs but excluded the creamy layer.\n\n5. **Application**:  \n   The creamy layer concept applies primarily to **OBCs** and not to Scheduled Castes (SCs) and Scheduled Tribes (STs).\n\n6. **Controversy**:  \n   The concept has been debated, with some arguing that it ensures equitable distribution of benefits, while others believe it dilutes the intent of reservation policies.\n\nBy excluding the creamy layer, the goal is to ensure that the **most marginalized** members of backward classes receive the benefits of affirmative action.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
